  Workflow:
  # 1. Flash fsr_11may.ino to ESP32
  # 2. Calibrate (once per patient/placement)
  python calibrate.py
  # 3. Record therapy sessions  
  python record.py -o sessions/session_001.csv --live
  # 4. Post-process
  python preprocess.py sessions/session_001.csv

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Run them sequentially, never simultaneously — each script needs exclusive
  access to the serial port.

  Here's the full workflow:

  ---
  Step 1 — Calibrate (once per patient/placement, ~2-3 hours)
  python calibrate.py
  # Choose option 1 → runs Phase 0 → 1 → 2 → fit
  # Choose option 2 → validation (Phase 3)  ← do this too
  # Choose option 3 → recheck baseline drift ← do this right before each 
  recording session
  # Choose q → quit
  This saves calibration_coeffs.json. Do this once and reuse it as long as:
  - Same patient, same body position, same strap tension
  - Session is ≤2 hours (recheck drift if longer)

  ---
  Step 2 — Recheck baseline before each recording session
  python calibrate.py   # option 3 only
  Quick ~2 min check. If any sensor drifted >2%, re-run option 1 for those
  sensors before recording.

  ---
  Step 3 — Record the therapy session
  python record.py -o sessions/session_001.csv --live
  # Ctrl+C when done
  Runs alone. --live shows real-time force numbers using the calibration from
  step 1.

  ---
  Step 4 — Post-process after recording is done
  python preprocess.py sessions/session_001.csv
  Run this after record.py has stopped. It reads the saved CSV and outputs
  sessions/session_001_forces.csv with F per sensor and F_calf / F_foot totals.

  ---
  Summary timeline:

  Day 1 (first time):
    calibrate.py → option 1 (calibrate) → option 2 (validate) → q

  Each therapy session:
    calibrate.py → option 3 (drift check) → q
    record.py    → record session → Ctrl+C
    preprocess.py → process the saved CSV

